  "prompt": "Is it illegal to conduct money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It is considered a **serious financial crime** and is punishable by law. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions to make it appear legitimate.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Illegal in most jurisdictions**: Laws against money laundering exist globally, often as part of broader anti-money laundering (AML) regulations.\n2. **Punishment**: Penalties for money laundering can include **heavy fines**, **asset forfeiture**, and **imprisonment**. The severity of the punishment depends on the jurisdiction and the scale of the operation.\n3. **Global cooperation**: International organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to combat money laundering through standardized regulations and cooperation between countries.\n4. **Related crimes**: Money laundering is often linked to other criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism financing.\n\nIf you suspect or are involved in money laundering, it is important to seek **legal advice** and understand the serious consequences of such actions.",
